<h2 id="Simple-Linear-Regression-Modeling">Simple Linear Regression Modeling<a class="anchor-link" href="#Simple-Linear-Regression-Modeling"> </a></h2>

</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p>You’ll learn the basics of this popular statistical model, what regression is, and how linear and logistic regressions differ. You’ll then learn how to fit simple linear regression models with numeric and categorical explanatory variables, and how to describe the relationship between the response and explanatory variables using model coefficients.</p>
</blockquote>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="A-tale-of-two-variables">A tale of two variables<a class="anchor-link" href="#A-tale-of-two-variables"> </a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Jargon</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li>Response variable (a.k.a. dependent variable)<ul>
<li>The variable that you want to predict.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Explanatory variables (a.k.a. independent variables)<ul>
<li>The variables that explain how the response variable will change.
<br></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Linear regression and logistic regression</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li>Linear regression<ul>
<li>The response variable is numeric.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Logistic regression<ul>
<li>The response variable is logical.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Simple linear/logistic regression<ul>
<li>There is only one explanatory variable.
<br></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Which one is the response variable?</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p><img src="/Data-Science-selfstudy-notes-Blog/images/copied_from_nb/./images/q1.PNG" alt="">
<br></p>

</div>

<h3 id="Fitting-a-linear-regression">Fitting a linear regression<a class="anchor-link" href="#Fitting-a-linear-regression"> </a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p><img src="/Data-Science-selfstudy-notes-Blog/images/copied_from_nb/./images/estimate_intercept.PNG" alt="">
<br></p>
<p><img src="/Data-Science-selfstudy-notes-Blog/images/copied_from_nb/./images/estimate_slope.PNG" alt=""></p>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Estimate the intercept</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p><img src="/Data-Science-selfstudy-notes-Blog/images/copied_from_nb/./images/estimate_intercept1.PNG" alt=""></p>

</div>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Estimate the slope</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p><img src="/Data-Science-selfstudy-notes-Blog/images/copied_from_nb/./images/estimate_slope2.PNG" alt=""></p>
<p><br></p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Linear regression with ols()</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>While <code>sns.regplot()</code> can display a linear regression trend line, it doesn't give you access to the intercept and slope as variables, or allow you to work with the model results as variables. That means that sometimes you'll need to run a linear regression yourself.</p>
<p>Time to run your first model!</p>
<p><code>taiwan_real_estate</code> is available. TWD is an abbreviation for Taiwan dollars.</p>
<p>In addition, for this exercise and the remainder of the course, the following packages will be imported and aliased if necessary:<code>matplotlib.pyplot as plt, seaborn as sns, and pandas as pd</code>.<br>
Instructions:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>Import the ols() function from the statsmodels.formula.api package.</li>
<li>Run a linear regression with price_twd_msq as the response variable, n_convenience as the explanatory variable, and taiwan_real_estate as the dataset. Name it mdl_price_vs_conv.</li>
<li>Fit the model.</li>
<li>Print the parameters of the fitted model.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Import the ols function</span>
<span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">statsmodels.formula.api</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">ols</span>

<span class="c1"># Create the model object</span>
<span class="n">mdl_price_vs_conv</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">ols</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">&quot;price_twd_msq ~ n_convenience&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">data</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">taiwan_real_estate</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Fit the model</span>
<span class="n">mdl_price_vs_conv</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">mdl_price_vs_conv</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># Print the parameters of the fitted model</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">mdl_price_vs_conv</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">params</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

<div class="output_area">

<div class="output_subarea output_stream output_stdout output_text">
<pre>Intercept        8.224237
n_convenience    0.798080
dtype: float64
</pre>
</div>
</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p><strong>Question</strong>: The model had an Intercept coefficient of 8.2242. What does this mean? <br></p>
<p><strong>Possible Answers:</strong> <br></p>
<ul>
<li><p>On average, houses had a price of 8.2242 TWD per square meter.</p>
</li>
<li><blockquote><p>On average, a house with zero convenience stores nearby had a price of 8.2242 TWD per square meter.</p>
</blockquote>
</li>
<li><p>The minimum house price was 8.2242 TWD per square meter.</p>
</li>
<li><p>The minimum house price with zero convenience stores nearby was 8.2242 TWD per square meter.</p>
</li>
<li><p>The intercept tells you nothing about house prices.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong>Question</strong>: The model had an n_convenience coefficient of 0.7981. What does this mean? <br></p>
<p><strong>Possible Answers:</strong> <br></p>
<ul>
<li><blockquote><p>If you increase the number of nearby convenience stores by one, then the expected increase in house price is 0.7981 TWD per square meter.</p>
</blockquote>
</li>
<li><p>If you increase the house price by 0.7981 TWD per square meter, then the expected increase in the number of nearby convenience stores is one.</p>
</li>
<li><p>If you increase the number of nearby convenience stores by 0.7981, then the expected increase in house price is one TWD per square meter.</p>
</li>
<li><p>If you increase the house price by one TWD per square meter, then the expected increase in the number of nearby convenience stores is 0.7981.</p>
</li>
<li><p>The n_convenience coefficient tells you nothing about house prices.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p>The intercept is positive, so a house with no convenience stores nearby still has a positive price. The coefficient for convenience stores is also positive, so as the number of nearby convenience stores increases, so does the price of the house.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Categorical-explanatory-variables">Categorical explanatory variables<a class="anchor-link" href="#Categorical-explanatory-variables"> </a></h3>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">

<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">seaborn</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">sns</span>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Visualizing numeric vs. categorical</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>If the explanatory variable is categorical, the scatter plot that you used before to visualize the data doesn't make sense. Instead, a good option is to draw a histogram for each category.</p>
<p>The Taiwan real estate dataset has a categorical variable in the form of the age of each house. The ages have been split into 3 groups:0 to 15 years, 15 to 30 years, and 30 to 45 years.</p>
<p>Instructions: <br></p>
<ul>
<li>Using taiwan_real_estate, plot a histogram of price_twd_msq with 10 bins. Split the plot by house_age_years to give 3 panels.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">rcParams</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;figure.figsize&#39;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">]</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">sns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">displot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">taiwan_real_estate</span><span class="p">,</span>
         <span class="n">x</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;price_twd_msq&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span>
         <span class="n">col</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;house_age_years&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span>
         <span class="n">bins</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Show the plot</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

<div class="output_area">



<div class="output_png output_subarea ">
<img src="data:image/png;base64,"
>
</div>

</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Calculating means by category</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>A good way to explore categorical variables further is to calculate summary statistics for each category. For example, you can calculate the mean and median of your response variable, grouped by a categorical variable. As such, you can compare each category in more detail.</p>
<p>Here, you'll look at grouped means for the house prices in the Taiwan real estate dataset. This will help you understand the output of a linear regression with a categorical variable.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">mean_price_by_age</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">taiwan_real_estate</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">groupby</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">&quot;house_age_years&quot;</span><span class="p">)[</span><span class="s2">&quot;price_twd_msq&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mean</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># Print the result</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">mean_price_by_age</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

<div class="output_area">

<div class="output_subarea output_stream output_stdout output_text">
<pre>house_age_years
0 to 15     12.637471
15 to 30     9.876743
30 to 45    11.393264
Name: price_twd_msq, dtype: float64
</pre>
</div>
</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Linear regression with a categorical explanatory variable</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Great job calculating those grouped means! As mentioned in the last video, the means of each category will also be the coefficients of a linear regression model with one categorical variable. You'll prove that in this exercise.</p>
<p>To run a linear regression model with categorical explanatory variables, you can use the same code as with numeric explanatory variables. The coefficients returned by the model are different, however. Here you'll run a linear regression on the Taiwan real estate dataset.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">mdl_price_vs_age</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">ols</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">&quot;price_twd_msq ~ house_age_years&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">data</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">taiwan_real_estate</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># Print the parameters of the fitted model</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">mdl_price_vs_age</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">params</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

<div class="output_area">

<div class="output_subarea output_stream output_stdout output_text">
<pre>Intercept                      12.637471
house_age_years[T.15 to 30]    -2.760728
house_age_years[T.30 to 45]    -1.244207
dtype: float64
</pre>
</div>
</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">mdl_price_vs_age0</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">ols</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">&quot;price_twd_msq ~ house_age_years + 0&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">data</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">taiwan_real_estate</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># Print the parameters of the fitted model</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">mdl_price_vs_age0</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">params</span><span class="p">)</span>

house_age_years[30 to 45]    11.393264
dtype: float64
</pre>
</div>
</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>The coefficients of the model are just the means of each category you calculated previously.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Predictions-and-model-objects">Predictions and model objects<a class="anchor-link" href="#Predictions-and-model-objects"> </a></h2><blockquote><p>In this chapter, you’ll discover how to use linear regression models to make predictions on Taiwanese house prices and Facebook advert clicks. You’ll also grow your regression skills as you get hands-on with model objects, understand the concept of "regression to the mean", and learn how to transform variables in a dataset.</p>
</blockquote>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Predicting house prices</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Perhaps the most useful feature of statistical models like linear regression is that you can make predictions. That is, you specify values for each of the explanatory variables, feed them to the model, and get a prediction for the corresponding response variable. The code flow is as follows. <br></p>
<div class="highlight"><pre><span></span><span class="n">explanatory_data</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">({</span><span class="s2">&quot;explanatory_var&quot;</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="n">list_of_values</span><span class="p">})</span><span class="n">predictions</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">model</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">predict</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">explanatory_data</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">prediction_data</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">explanatory_data</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">assign</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">response_var</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">predictions</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>
<p><br>
Here, you'll make predictions for the house prices in the Taiwan real estate dataset.</p>
<p><strong>taiwan_real_estate</strong> is available. The fitted linear regression model of house price versus number of convenience stores is available as <strong>mdl_price_vs_conv</strong>. For future exercises, when a model is available, it will also be fitted.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">numpy</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">np</span>

<span class="c1"># Create explanatory_data </span>
<span class="n">explanatory_data</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">({</span><span class="s1">&#39;n_convenience&#39;</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">arange</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">11</span><span class="p">)})</span>

<span class="c1"># Use mdl_price_vs_conv to predict with explanatory_data, call it price_twd_msq</span>
<span class="n">price_twd_msq</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">mdl_price_vs_conv</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">predict</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">explanatory_data</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Create prediction_data</span>
<span class="n">prediction_data</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">explanatory_data</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">assign</span><span class="p">(</span>
    <span class="n">price_twd_msq</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">price_twd_msq</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Print the result</span>
<span class="n">display</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">prediction_data</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output">

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>The limits of prediction</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>In the last exercise, you made predictions on some sensible, could-happen-in-real-life, situations. That is, the cases when the number of nearby convenience stores were between zero and ten. To test the limits of the model's ability to predict, try some impossible situations.</p>
<p>Use the console to try predicting house prices from <strong>mdl_price_vs_conv</strong> when there are -1 convenience stores. Do the same for 2.5 convenience stores. What happens in each case?</p>
<p><strong>mdl_price_vs_conv</strong> is available.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">impossible</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">({</span><span class="s1">&#39;n_convenience&#39;</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mf">2.5</span><span class="p">]})</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">mdl_price_vs_conv</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">predict</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">impossible</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

<div class="output_area">



<div class="output_text output_subarea output_execute_result">
<pre>0     7.426158
1    10.219437
dtype: float64</pre>
</div>

</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p><strong>Question</strong>: Try making predictions on your two impossible cases. What happens?</p>
<p>Possible Answers:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>The model throws an error because these cases are impossible in real life.</p>
</li>
<li><p>The model throws a warning because these cases are impossible in real life.</p>
</li>
<li><blockquote><p>The model successfully gives a prediction about cases that are impossible in real life.</p>
</blockquote>
</li>
<li><p>The model throws an error for -1 stores because it violates the assumptions of a linear regression. 2.5 stores gives a successful prediction.</p>
</li>
<li><p>The model throws an error for 2.5 stores because it violates the assumptions of a linear regression. -1 stores gives a successful prediction.
<br></p>
</li>
</ul>
<p>Linear models don't know what is possible or not in real life. That means that they can give you predictions that don't make any sense when applied to your data. You need to understand what your data means in order to determine whether a prediction is nonsense or not.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Manually predicting house prices</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>You can manually calculate the predictions from the model coefficients. When making predictions in real life, it is better to use <strong>.predict()</strong>, but doing this manually is helpful to reassure yourself that predictions aren't magic - they are simply arithmetic.</p>
<p>In fact, for a simple linear regression, the predicted value is just the intercept plus the slope times the explanatory variable.</p>
<p>$$response = intercept + slope * explanatory$$</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">explanatory_data</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">({</span><span class="s1">&#39;n_convenience&#39;</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">arange</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">)})</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">coeffs</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">mdl_price_vs_conv</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">params</span>

<span class="c1"># Get the intercept</span>
<span class="n">intercept</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">coeffs</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span>

<span class="c1"># Get the slope</span>
<span class="n">slope</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">coeffs</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]</span>

<span class="c1"># Manually calculate the predictions</span>
<span class="n">price_twd_msq</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">intercept</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">slope</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="n">explanatory_data</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">price_twd_msq</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Compare to the results from .predict()</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">price_twd_msq</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">assign</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">predictions_auto</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">mdl_price_vs_conv</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">predict</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">explanatory_data</span><span class="p">)))</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Regression to the mean</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>The concept:- Response value = fitted value + residual- "The stuff you explained" + "the stuff you couldn't explain"</p>
<ul>
<li>Residuals exist due to problems in the model and fundamental randomness</li>
<li>Extreme cases are often due to randomness</li>
<li>Regression to the mean means extreme cases don't persist over time</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Home run!</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Regression to the mean is an important concept in many areas, including sports.</p>
<p>Here you can see a dataset of baseball batting data in 2017 and 2018. Each point represents a player, and more home runs are better. A naive prediction might be that the performance in 2018 is the same as the performance in 2017. That is, a linear regression would lie on the "y equals x" line.</p>
<p>Explore the plot and make predictions. What does regression to the mean say about the number of home runs in 2018 for a player who was very successful in 2017?</p>
<p><img src="/Data-Science-selfstudy-notes-Blog/images/copied_from_nb/./images/homerun.PNG" alt="">
<br></p>
<p>Someone who hit 40 home runs in 2017 is predicted to hit 10 fewer home runs the next year because regression to the mean states that, on average, extremely high values are not sustained.</p>
<p>Due to regression to the mean, it's common that one player or team that does really well one year, doesn't do as well the next. Likewise players or teams that perform very badly one year do better the next year.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Plotting consecutive portfolio returns</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Regression to the mean is also an important concept in investing. Here you'll look at the annual returns from investing in companies in the Standard and Poor 500 index (S&amp;P 500), in 2018 and 2019.</p>
<p>The sp500_yearly_returns dataset contains three columns:<br></p>
<table>
<thead><tr>
<th><strong>variable</strong></th>
<th><strong>meaning</strong></th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>symbol</td>
<td>Stock ticker symbol uniquely identifying the company.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>return_2018</td>
<td>A measure of investment performance in 2018.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>return_2019</td>
<td>A measure of investment performance in 2019.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><br></p>
<p>A positive number for the return means the investment increased in value; negative means it lost value.</p>
<p>Just as with baseball home runs, a naive prediction might be that the investment performance stays the same from year to year, lying on the y equals x line.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">sp500_yearly_returns</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">&quot;./datasets/sp500_yearly_returns.csv&quot;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">sp500_yearly_returns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">info</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">

<div class="output_area">

<div class="output_subarea output_stream output_stdout output_text">

</div>

    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">fig</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">figure</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># Plot the first layer: y = x</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">axline</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">xy1</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">),</span> <span class="n">slope</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">linewidth</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">color</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;green&quot;</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Add scatter plot with linear regression trend line</span>
<span class="n">sns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">regplot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;return_2018&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="n">y</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;return_2019&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span>

<span class="c1"># Set the axes so that the distances along the x and y axes look the same</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">axis</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">&quot;equal&quot;</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Show the plot</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">

    {% endraw %}

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>The regression trend line looks very different to the y equals x line. As the financial advisors say, "Past performance is no guarantee of future results."</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Modeling consecutive returns</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Let's quantify the relationship between returns in 2019 and 2018 by running a linear regression and making predictions. By looking at companies with extremely high or extremely low returns in 2018, we can see if their performance was similar in 2019.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">mdl_returns</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">ols</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">&quot;return_2019 ~ return_2018&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">data</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">sp500_yearly_returns</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># Print the parameters</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">mdl_returns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">params</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

<div class="output_area">

<div class="output_subarea output_stream output_stdout output_text">
<pre>Intercept      0.321321
return_2018    0.020069
dtype: float64
</pre>
</div>
</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>

    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">mdl_returns</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">ols</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">&quot;return_2019 ~ return_2018&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">data</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">sp500_yearly_returns</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># Create a DataFrame with return_2018 at -1, 0, and 1 </span>
<span class="n">explanatory_data</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">({</span><span class="s2">&quot;return_2018&quot;</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]})</span>

<span class="c1"># Use mdl_returns to predict with explanatory_data</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">mdl_returns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">predict</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">explanatory_data</span><span class="p">))</span>
</pre></div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Investments that gained a lot in value in 2018 on average gained only a small amount in 2019. Similarly, investments that lost a lot of value in 2018 on average also gained a small amount in 2019.</p>

</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Transforming the explanatory variable</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>If there is no straight-line relationship between the response variable and the explanatory variable, it is sometimes possible to create one by transforming one or both of the variables. Here, you'll look at transforming the explanatory variable.</p>
<p>You'll take another look at the Taiwan real estate dataset, this time using the distance to the nearest MRT (metro) station as the explanatory variable. You'll use code to make every commuter's dream come true:shortening the distance to the metro station by taking the square root. Take that, geography!</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">taiwan_real_estate</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;sqrt_dist_to_mrt_m&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sqrt</span><span class="p">(</span>
<span class="n">taiwan_real_estate</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;dist_to_mrt_m&quot;</span><span class="p">])</span>


<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">figure</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># Plot using the transformed variable</span>
<span class="n">sns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">regplot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;sqrt_dist_to_mrt_m&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="n">y</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;price_twd_msq&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="n">data</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">taiwan_real_estate</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="n">ci</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">None</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

<div class="output_area">

>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">

<span class="n">mdl_price_vs_dist</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">ols</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">&quot;price_twd_msq ~ sqrt_dist_to_mrt_m&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">data</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">taiwan_real_estate</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># Create prediction_data by adding a column of predictions to explantory_data</span>
<span class="n">prediction_data</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">explanatory_data</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">assign</span><span class="p">(</span>
    <span class="n">price_twd_msq</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">mdl_price_vs_dist</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">predict</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">explanatory_data</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Print the result</span>
<span class="n">display</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">prediction_data</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Transforming the response variable too</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>The response variable can be transformed too, but this means you need an extra step at the end to undo that transformation. That is, you "back transform" the predictions.</p>
<p>In the video, you saw the first step of the digital advertising workflow:spending money to buy ads, and counting how many people see them (the "impressions"). The next step is determining how many people click on the advert after seeing it.</p>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Assessing-model-fit">Assessing model fit<a class="anchor-link" href="#Assessing-model-fit"> </a></h2><blockquote><p>In this chapter, you’ll learn how to ask questions of your model to assess fit. You’ll learn how to quantify how well a linear regression model fits, diagnose model problems using visualizations, and understand each observation's leverage and influence to create the model. <br></p>
</blockquote>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Quantifying-model-fit">Quantifying model fit<a class="anchor-link" href="#Quantifying-model-fit"> </a></h3><p><strong>Coefficient of determination</strong><br></p>
<p>Sometimes called "r-squared" or "R-squared".</p>
<blockquote><p>The proportion of the variance in the response variable that is predictable from the
explanatory variable.</p>
<ul>
<li>1 means a perfect fit</li>
<li>0 means the worst possible fit</li>
</ul>
</blockquote>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">mdl_bream</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">ols</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">&quot;mass_g ~ length_cm&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">data</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">bream</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="n">display</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">mdl_bream</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">summary</span><span class="p">())</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p><strong>Residual standard error (RSE)</strong><br></p>
<p><img src="/Data-Science-selfstudy-notes-Blog/images/copied_from_nb/./images/rse.PNG" alt=""></p>
<ul>
<li>A "typical" difference between a prediction and an observed response</li>
<li>It has the same unit as the response variable.</li>
<li>$MSE = RSE^2$</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">

<div class="inner_cell">

<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">mse</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">mdl_bream</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mse_resid</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;mse: &#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">mse</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">rse</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sqrt</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">mse</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">&quot;rse: &quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">rse</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Coefficient of determination</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>The coefficient of determination is a measure of how well the linear regression line fits the observed values. For simple linear regression, it is equal to the square of the correlation between the explanatory and response variables.</p>
<p>Here, you'll take another look at the second stage of the advertising pipeline:modeling the click response to impressions. Two models are available: <strong>mdl_click_vs_impression_orig</strong> models <strong>n_clicks</strong> versus <strong>n_impressions</strong>. mdl_click_vs_impression_trans is the transformed model you saw in Chapter 2. It models <strong>n_clicks</strong> to the power of 0.25 versus <strong>n_impressions</strong> to the power of 0.25.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<span class="n">mdl_click_vs_impression_trans</span><span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">mdl_click_vs_impression</span> <span class="o">=</span>  <span class="n">ols</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">&quot;qdrt_n_clicks ~ qdrt_n_impressions&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">data</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">ad_conversion</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">()</span>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p><strong>Question:</strong> mdl_click_vs_impression_orig has a coefficient of determination of 0.89. Which statement about the model is true?</p>
<p><strong>Possible Answers</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><p>The number of clicks explains 89% of the variability in the number of impressions.</p>
</li>
<li><blockquote><p>The number of impressions explains 89% of the variability in the number of clicks.</p>
</blockquote>
</li>
<li><p>The model is correct 89% of the time.</p>
</li>
<li><p>The correlation between the number of impressions and the number of clicks is 0.89.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p>The transformed model has a higher coefficient of determination than the original model, suggesting that it gives a better fit to the data.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Residual standard error</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Residual standard error (RSE) is a measure of the typical size of the residuals. Equivalently, it's a measure of how wrong you can expect predictions to be. Smaller numbers are better, with zero being a perfect fit to the data.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">mse_orig</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">mdl_click_vs_impression_orig</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mse_resid</span>

<span class="c1"># Calculate rse_orig for mdl_click_vs_impression_orig and print it</span>
<span class="n">rse_orig</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sqrt</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">mse_orig</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">&quot;RSE of original model: &quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">rse_orig</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Calculate mse_trans for mdl_click_vs_impression_trans</span>
<span class="n">mse_trans</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">mdl_click_vs_impression_trans</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mse_resid</span>

<span class="c1"># Calculate rse_trans for mdl_click_vs_impression_trans and print it</span>
<span class="n">rse_trans</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sqrt</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">mse_trans</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">&quot;RSE of transformed model: &quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">rse_trans</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

<div class="output_area">

<div class="output_subarea output_stream output_stdout output_text">
<pre>RSE of original model:  19.905838862478138
RSE of transformed model:  0.19690640896875727
</pre>
</div>
</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p><strong>Question</strong>: <em>mdl_click_vs_impression_orig</em> has an RSE of about 20. Which statement is true?</p>
<p>Possible Answers:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>The model explains 20% of the variability in the number of clicks.</p>
</li>
<li><p>20% of the residuals are typically greater than the observed values.</p>
</li>
<li><blockquote><p>The typical difference between observed number of clicks and predicted number of clicks is 20.</p>
</blockquote>
</li>
<li><p>The typical difference between observed number of impressions and predicted number of impressions is 20.</p>
</li>
<li><p>The model predicts that you get one click for every 20 observed impressions.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Note</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li>Since mdl_click_vs_impression_orig has an RSE of about 20, mdl_click_vs_impression_trans has an RSE of about 0.2.). The transformed model - mdl_click_vs_impression_trans gives more accurate predictions. </li>
<li>RSE is a measure of accuracy for regression models. It even works on other other statistical model types like regression trees, so you can compare accuracy across different classes of models.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Q-Q plot of residuals</strong></p>
</blockquote>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Leverage</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Leverage measures how unusual or extreme the explanatory variables are for each observation. Very roughly, high leverage means that the explanatory variable has values that are different from other points in the dataset. In the case of simple linear regression, where there is only one explanatory value, this typically means values with a very high or very low explanatory value.</p>
<p>Here, you'll look at highly leveraged values in the model of house price versus the square root of distance from the nearest MRT station in the Taiwan real estate dataset.<br></p>
<p><img src="/Data-Science-selfstudy-notes-Blog/images/copied_from_nb/./images/leverage.PNG" alt=""> <br></p>
<p>Guess which observations you think will have a high leverage, then move the slider to find out.</p>
<p>Which statement is true?</p>
<blockquote><p>Observations with a large distance to the nearest MRT station have the highest leverage, because most of the observations have a short distance, so long distances are more extreme.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Highly leveraged points are the ones with explanatory variables that are furthest away from the others.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Influence</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Influence measures how much a model would change if each observation was left out of the model calculations, one at a time. That is, it measures how different the prediction line would look if you would run a linear regression on all data points except that point, compared to running a linear regression on the whole dataset.</p>
<p>The standard metric for influence is Cook's distance, which calculates influence based on the residual size and the leverage of the point.<br></p>
<p><img src="/Data-Science-selfstudy-notes-Blog/images/copied_from_nb/./images/influence.PNG" alt=""><br></p>
<p>You can see the same model as last time:house price versus the square root of distance from the nearest MRT station in the Taiwan real estate dataset.
Guess which observations you think will have a high influence, then move the slider to find out.</p>
<p>Which statement is true?</p>
<blockquote><p>Observations far away from the trend line have high influence, because they have large residuals and are far away from other observations.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>The majority of the influential houses were those with prices that were much higher than the model predicted (and one with a price that was much lower).</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Extracting leverage and influence</strong></p>
</blockquote>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">taiwan_real_estate</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;sqrt_dist_to_mrt_m&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sqrt</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">taiwan_real_estate</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;dist_to_mrt_m&quot;</span><span class="p">])</span>

<span class="c1"># Run a linear regression of price_twd_msq vs. sqrt_dist_to_mrt_m</span>
<span class="n">mdl_price_vs_dist</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">ols</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">&quot;price_twd_msq ~ sqrt_dist_to_mrt_m&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">data</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">taiwan_real_estate</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

In the video, until you saw the trend line, it wasn't clear how the explanatory variable was distributed on each line. This can be solved with a histogram of the explanatory variable, grouped by the response.</p>
<p>You will use these histograms to get to know the financial services churn dataset seen in the video.</p>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Visualizing linear and logistic models</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>As with linear regressions, regplot() will draw model predictions for a logistic regression without you having to worry about the modeling code yourself. To see how the predictions differ for linear and logistic regressions, try drawing both trend lines side by side. Spoiler:you should see a linear (straight line) trend from the linear model, and a logistic (S-shaped) trend from the logistic model.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">sns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">regplot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;time_since_first_purchase&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="n">y</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;has_churned&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="n">data</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">churn</span><span class="p">,</span> 
            <span class="n">ci</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">None</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="n">line_kws</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">{</span><span class="s2">&quot;color&quot;</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="s2">&quot;red&quot;</span><span class="p">})</span>

<span class="c1"># Draw a logistic regression trend line and a scatter plot of time_since_first_purchase vs. has_churned</span>
<span class="n">sns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">regplot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;time_since_first_purchase&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="n">y</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;has_churned&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="n">data</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">churn</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="n">ci</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">None</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="n">logistic</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="n">line_kws</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">{</span><span class="s2">&quot;color&quot;</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="s2">&quot;blue&quot;</span><span class="p">})</span>

<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Logistic regression with logit()</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Logistic regression requires another function from statsmodels.formula.api:logit(). It takes the same arguments as ols(): a formula and data argument. You then use .fit() to fit the model to the data.
Here, you'll model how the length of relationship with a customer affects churn.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Import logit</span>
<span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">statsmodels.formula.api</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">logit</span>

<span class="c1"># Fit a logistic regression of churn vs. </span>
<span class="c1"># length of relationship using the churn dataset</span>
<span class="n">mdl_churn_vs_relationship</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">logit</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;has_churned~time_since_first_purchase&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">data</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">churn</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># Print the parameters of the fitted model</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">mdl_churn_vs_relationship</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">params</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

<div class="output_area">

<div class="output_subarea output_stream output_stdout output_text">

         Iterations 4
Intercept                   -0.015185
time_since_first_purchase   -0.354795
dtype: float64
</pre>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Predictions-and-odds-ratios">Predictions and odds ratios<a class="anchor-link" href="#Predictions-and-odds-ratios"> </a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Probabilities</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>There are four main ways of expressing the prediction from a logistic regression model – we'll look at each of them over the next four exercises. Firstly, since the response variable is either "yes" or "no", you can make a prediction of the probability of a "yes". Here, you'll calculate and visualize these probabilities.</p>
<p>Two variables are available:<br></p>
<ul>
<li>mdl_churn_vs_relationship is the fitted logistic regression model of has_churned versus time_since_first_purchase.</li>
<li>explanatory_data is a DataFrame of explanatory values.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">explanatory_data</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">({</span><span class="s1">&#39;time_since_first_purchase&#39;</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">arange</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="mf">1.5</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mf">4.1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="o">.</span><span class="mi">25</span><span class="p">)})</span>
<span class="c1"># explanatory_data</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">prediction_data</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">explanatory_data</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">assign</span><span class="p">(</span>
  <span class="n">has_churned</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">mdl_churn_vs_relationship</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">predict</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">explanatory_data</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Print the head</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">prediction_data</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">head</span><span class="p">())</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>

    <span class="n">has_churned</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">mdl_churn_vs_relationship</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">predict</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">explanatory_data</span><span class="p">)</span>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Most likely outcome</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>When explaining your results to a non-technical audience, you may wish to side-step talking about probabilities and simply explain the most likely outcome. That is, rather than saying there is a 60% chance of a customer churning, you say that the most likely outcome is that the customer will churn. The trade-off here is easier interpretation at the cost of nuance.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">

<span class="c1"># Print the head</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">prediction_data</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">head</span><span class="p">())</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output">

<div class="output_area">

    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">prediction_data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;most_likely_outcome&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">round</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">prediction_data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;has_churned&quot;</span><span class="p">])</span>

<span class="n">fig</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">figure</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># Create a scatter plot with logistic trend line (from previous exercise)</span>
<span class="n">sns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">regplot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;time_since_first_purchase&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="n">y</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;has_churned&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="n">data</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">churn</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="n">ci</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">None</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="n">logistic</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Overlay with prediction_data, colored red</span>
<span class="n">sns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">scatterplot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;time_since_first_purchase&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span>
                <span class="n">y</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;most_likely_outcome&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span>
                <span class="n">data</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">prediction_data</span><span class="p">,</span>
                <span class="n">color</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;red&quot;</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

>

</div>

</div>

    {% endraw %}

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Odds ratio</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Odds ratios compare the probability of something happening with the probability of it not happening. This is sometimes easier to reason about than probabilities, particularly when you want to make decisions about choices. For example, if a customer has a 20% chance of churning, it may be more intuitive to say "the chance of them not churning is four times higher than the chance of them churning".</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">prediction_data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;odds_ratio&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">prediction_data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;has_churned&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">/</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="n">prediction_data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;has_churned&quot;</span><span class="p">])</span>

<span class="c1"># Print the head</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">prediction_data</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">head</span><span class="p">())</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

<div class="output_area">

<div class="output_subarea output_stream output_stdout output_text">

</pre>
</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

<span class="n">sns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">lineplot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;time_since_first_purchase&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">y</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;odds_ratio&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">data</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">prediction_data</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Add a dotted horizontal line at odds_ratio = 1</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">axhline</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">y</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">linestyle</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;dotted&quot;</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Show the plot</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Odds ratios provide an alternative to probabilities that make it easier to compare positive and negative responses.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<blockquote><p><strong>Log odds ratio</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>One downside to probabilities and odds ratios for logistic regression predictions is that the prediction lines for each are curved. This makes it harder to reason about what happens to the prediction when you make a change to the explanatory variable. The logarithm of the odds ratio (the "log odds ratio" or "logit") does have a linear relationship between predicted response and explanatory variable. That means that as the explanatory variable changes, you don't see dramatic changes in the response metric - only linear changes.</p>
<p>Since the actual values of log odds ratio are less intuitive than (linear) odds ratio, for visualization purposes it's usually better to plot the odds ratio and apply a log transformation to the y-axis scale.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">prediction_data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;log_odds_ratio&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">log</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">prediction_data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;odds_ratio&#39;</span><span class="p">])</span>

<span class="c1"># Print the head</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">prediction_data</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">head</span><span class="p">())</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

<div class="output_area">

<div class="output_subarea output_stream output_stdout output_text">
<pre>   time_since_first_purchase  has_churned  most_likely_outcome  odds_ratio  log_odds_ratio
0                      -1.50     0.626448                  1.0    1.677003        0.517008
1                      -1.25     0.605470                  1.0    1.534661        0.428309
2                      -1.00     0.584096                  1.0    1.404400        0.339610
3                      -0.75     0.562401                  1.0    1.285197        0.250912
4                      -0.50     0.540465                  1.0    1.176111        0.162213
</pre>
</div>
</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">prediction_data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;log_odds_ratio&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">log</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">prediction_data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;odds_ratio&quot;</span><span class="p">])</span>

<span class="n">fig</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">figure</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># Update the line plot: log_odds_ratio vs. time_since_first_purchase</span>
<span class="n">sns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">lineplot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;time_since_first_purchase&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span>
             <span class="n">y</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;log_odds_ratio&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span>
             <span class="n">data</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">prediction_data</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Add a dotted horizontal line at log_odds_ratio = 0</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">axhline</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">y</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">linestyle</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;dotted&quot;</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

<div class="output_area">

>
